<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bignoniaceae" genus="Dolichandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dolichandra uncata" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="uncata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">Dolichandra uncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs predominantly in riverbanks, swamps and mangroves, presenting seeds that are corky and supposedly adapted for water dispersal (
<bibRefCitation author="Gentry, AH" journalOrPublisher="Brittonia" pageId="6" pageNumber="41" pagination="226 - 242" publicationUrl="10.2307/2805585" refId="B4" refString="Gentry, AH, 1973b. Generic delimitations of Central American Bignoniaceae. Brittonia 25: 226 - 242, DOI: 10.2307/2805585" title="Generic delimitations of Central American Bignoniaceae." url="10.2307/2805585" volume="25" year="1973 b">Gentry 1973b</bibRefCitation>
). On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. H. Fonseca &amp; L. G. Lohmann" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Fonseca &amp; Cabral &amp; Agra &amp; Lohmann" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bignoniaceae" genus="Dolichandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dolichandra hispida" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hispida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">Dolichandra hispida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more common in non-flooded areas, presenting seeds adapted to wind dispersal.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="39" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="39">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. H. Fonseca &amp; L. G. Lohmann" authorityYear="2015" baseAuthorityName="Fonseca &amp; Cabral &amp; Agra &amp; Lohmann" baseAuthorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bignoniaceae" genus="Dolichandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dolichandra hispida" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="hispida">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">Dolichandra hispida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in southern, southwestern and central Brazil, Paraguay and Bolivia, whereas 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Bignoniaceae" genus="Dolichandra" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Dolichandra uncata" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="39" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="uncata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="39">Dolichandra uncata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has its northern limit in Mexico and southern limit in Argentina and Uruguay (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Distribution of Dolichandra hispida (red dots) and Dolichandra uncata (blue dots)." pageId="4" pageNumber="39">2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
